---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { buildRepoTags, fetchPublicRepos, formatDate } from '../lib/github';

const repos = await fetchPublicRepos();
const featuredRepos = repos.slice(0, 10);

const now = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {
	dateStyle: 'long',
	timeStyle: 'short',
	timeZone: 'America/New_York',
}).format(new Date());
---

<Layout
	title="gvillarroel Public Projects"
	description="Static documentation hub for public gvillarroel repositories, generated with Astro and deployed to Google Cloud Storage."
>
	<div class="page-shell">
		<header class="site-header">
			<div>
				<div class="site-title">gvillarroel / static docs</div>
				<div class="site-tagline">Public repository documentation and integration examples baked into static HTML for bucket hosting.</div>
			</div>
			<div class="cta-row" style="margin-top: 0;">
				<a class="button-link" href="/integrations.html">Integration examples</a>
				<a class="button-link" href="/datasets.html">Dataset dashboards</a>
				<a class="button-link" href="https://github.com/gvillarroel">GitHub profile</a>
			</div>
		</header>

		<div class="grid-shell">
			<aside class="sidebar">
				<div class="kicker">Repository Nav</div>
				<strong>Public projects</strong>
				<ul class="repo-list">
					{
						repos.map((repo) => (
							<li>
								<a href={`projects/${repo.slug}.html`}>
									<span class="repo-name">{repo.name}</span>
									<span class="repo-meta">{repo.description}</span>
								</a>
							</li>
						))
					}
				</ul>
			</aside>

			<main class="panel">
				<div class="kicker">Static Site Built With Astro</div>
				<h1 class="hero-title">This site is assembled before publishing and then served as static files.</h1>
				<p class="lead">
					If you have never used Astro, the simplest mental model is a page factory. During the build,
					Astro takes templates, content, and data, turns them into ready-to-serve HTML/CSS/JS, and writes
					the final result into <code>dist/</code>. After that, the bucket only serves static files; there is
					no application server rebuilding pages for each visitor.
				</p>
				<div class="stats">
					<div class="stat">
						<strong>Repositories</strong>
						<span>{repos.length} public projects indexed</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat">
						<strong>Publishing</strong>
						<span>Astro static build on GCS</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat">
						<strong>Input model</strong>
						<span>Data and content gathered during the build</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat">
						<strong>Generated pages</strong>
						<span>Repos, integrations, and documentation</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat">
						<strong>Datasets</strong>
						<span>CSV and Parquet summaries with Plotly charts</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat">
						<strong>Last build</strong>
						<span>{now}</span>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="cta-row">
					<a class="button-link" href="#static-delivery-model">Read the step-by-step walkthrough</a>
					<a class="button-link" href="/integrations.html">Browse integrations</a>
					<a class="button-link" href="/datasets.html">Browse datasets</a>
					<a class="button-link" href="https://github.com/gvillarroel/astro-gcs">Source code</a>
				</div>

				<section class="integration-section" id="static-delivery-model">
					<div class="section-heading">
						<div class="kicker">Step By Step</div>
						<h2>How this site works, from raw inputs to the final published HTML.</h2>
						<p class="section-summary">
							This section explains the full flow as if the reader knows nothing about Astro. The key
							idea is that this project can accept changing inputs, but the published result is still a
							set of static files. The intermediate steps are what gather, transform, and convert that
							information into web pages.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="card-grid">
						<article class="card">
							<strong>Step 1: new information appears</strong>
							<p>
								Some local or external process makes new information available: GitHub metadata,
								generated Markdown, synchronized content from other sources, or <code>CSV</code> and
								<code>Parquet</code> files that need summaries and charts.
							</p>
						</article>
						<article class="card">
							<strong>Step 2: scripts prepare the material</strong>
							<p>
								Before the site is built, scripts read those sources, transform them, and leave
								everything ready for Astro. This is where repository pages, integration pages, dataset
								summaries, and chart configs get prepared.
							</p>
						</article>
						<article class="card">
							<strong>Step 3: Astro assembles the site</strong>
							<p>
								Astro takes templates, Markdown, JSON, and already-prepared data, then turns them into
								HTML pages, CSS styles, and JavaScript. In other words, Astro acts as the assembler that
								converts scattered inputs into a navigable site.
							</p>
						</article>
						<article class="card">
							<strong>Step 4: the final folder is written</strong>
							<p>
								The build result is written to <code>dist/</code>. That folder already contains the GitHub
								metadata pages, the integration pages, the dataset views built from <code>CSV</code> and
								<code>Parquet</code>, and the Plotly-based charts ready to render.
							</p>
						</article>
						<article class="card">
							<strong>Step 5: the bucket serves static files</strong>
							<p>
								Once published, Google Cloud Storage only serves files that were generated earlier.
								There is no Astro SSR, no live backend building pages on demand, and no fresh call to the
								original data source every time a user visits.
							</p>
						</article>
						<article class="card">
							<strong>How updates happen</strong>
							<p>
								This flow can run once a day, once a week, manually whenever needed, or from a GitHub
								Action triggered by a schedule or by the arrival of new data.
							</p>
						</article>
					</div>

					<div class="docs docs-markdown">
						<h3>Step 1. Data and content enter from several places</h3>
						<p>
							This project does not depend on a single source. Before the build starts, several kinds of
							input can appear: public GitHub metadata, local Markdown, remote Markdown, synchronized
							content from external processes, and <code>CSV</code> or <code>Parquet</code> files. At this
							point, none of that is a web page yet. Astro and the project scripts take those inputs and
							turn them into navigable pages during the build. Astro’s official documentation on content
							and build-time data loading describes this idea of working with data before the final render:
							<a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/reference/content-loader-reference/"> Content Loader API</a>,
							<a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/reference/modules/astro-content/"> Astro Content API</a>,
							y <a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/basics/astro-pages/"> Astro Pages</a>.
						</p>
						<pre data-language="mermaid"><code>{`flowchart LR
    A["GitHub metadata"] --> E["Build inputs"]
    B["Local and remote Markdown"] --> E
    C["Knowledge sync"] --> E
    D["CSV and Parquet"] --> E
    E --> F["Project scripts read and organize everything"]
`}</code></pre>

						<h3>Step 2. Scripts convert raw inputs into Astro-ready material</h3>
						<p>
							This is where a large part of the work we did actually happens. The scripts do not publish
							the site on their own; they first produce a cleaner intermediate layer. In this repository,
							that includes generating uniform repository pages, normalizing generated Markdown, reading
							datasets from <code>CSV</code> and <code>Parquet</code>, summarizing columns, preparing preview
							rows, and generating Plotly configs. By the time Astro starts rendering pages, it receives
							much cleaner structures. That fits Astro’s official build-time routing model, including
							<a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/reference/errors/get-static-paths-required/"> getStaticPaths()</a>
							and file-based pages inside <code>src/pages</code>.
						</p>
						<pre data-language="mermaid"><code>{`flowchart TD
    A["Raw inputs"] --> B["scripts/generate-integrations.mjs"]
    B --> C["Generated Markdown"]
    B --> D["Dataset JSON"]
    B --> E["Summaries and chart configs"]
    C --> F["Astro receives prepared content"]
    D --> F
    E --> F
`}</code></pre>

						<h3>Step 3. Astro takes templates, data, and content, then builds pages</h3>
						<p>
							If someone knows nothing about Astro, the simplest explanation here is this: Astro is the
							site builder. It takes components, templates, pages, Markdown, and already-prepared data,
							then converts them into ready-to-serve HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. In the official docs,
							Astro explains that <code>static</code> mode prerenders pages during the build and that the
							default output directory is <code>dist/</code>. This project also uses
							<code>build.format = 'file'</code>, which is why the final routes are concrete HTML files.
							Official references:
							<a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/basics/rendering-modes/"> Rendering Modes</a>,
							<a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/reference/configuration-reference/#outdir"> outDir</a>,
							<a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/reference/configuration-reference/#buildformat"> build.format</a>,
							y <a href="https://v4.docs.astro.build/en/install-and-setup/"> Astro build output</a>.
						</p>
						<pre data-language="mermaid"><code>{`flowchart TD
    A[".astro templates"] --> D["Astro build"]
    B["Generated Markdown and content"] --> D
    C["Prepared JSON and data"] --> D
    D --> E["HTML"]
    D --> F["CSS"]
    D --> G["JavaScript"]
    E --> H["dist/"]
    F --> H
    G --> H
`}</code></pre>

						<h3>Step 4. What lands in dist/ is already the final site</h3>
						<p>
							The <code>dist/</code> folder matters because it cleanly separates the build process from the
							published result. Once Astro finishes, <code>dist/</code> already contains what the user will
							consume: HTML pages, assets, stylesheets, and scripts. In our case, that includes repository
							pages, the integrations section, dataset views, and the client-side pieces needed for Mermaid
							and Plotly. Astro’s CLI documentation also explains that preview serves the static output from
							<code>dist/</code>:
							<a href="https://v4.docs.astro.build/es/reference/cli-reference/"> Astro CLI reference</a>.
						</p>
						<pre data-language="mermaid"><code>{`flowchart LR
    A["Astro finishes the build"] --> B["dist/index.html"]
    A --> C["dist/integrations.html"]
    A --> D["dist/datasets.html"]
    A --> E["dist/projects/*.html"]
    A --> F["dist/_astro/*"]
`}</code></pre>

						<h3>Step 5. Google Cloud Storage does not rebuild anything</h3>
						<p>
							Once we upload <code>dist/</code> to the bucket, Google Cloud Storage acts as static website
							hosting. That means it serves HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files that were generated earlier.
							The official Cloud Storage docs explicitly say it can host static websites with client-side
							technologies like HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, but not server-side dynamic content. That is
							exactly why this project can accept changing inputs and still publish as a static site:
							<a href="https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/hosting-static-website"> Host a static website on Cloud Storage</a>.
						</p>
						<pre data-language="mermaid"><code>{`flowchart TD
    A["Local dist/ output"] --> B["deploy-gcs.ps1"]
    B --> C["Cloud Storage bucket"]
    C --> D["The browser requests index.html"]
    C --> E["The browser requests CSS / JS / images"]
    C --> F["There is no real-time server-side rendering"]
`}</code></pre>

						<h3>What we generated in this project</h3>
						<ul>
							<li><strong>Repository pages:</strong> generated from public GitHub metadata.</li>
							<li><strong>Integration pages:</strong> generated from local Markdown, remote Markdown, and synced content.</li>
							<li><strong>Dataset pages:</strong> generated from <code>CSV</code> and <code>Parquet</code> files.</li>
							<li><strong>Charts:</strong> Plotly renders visualizations prepared from build-time dataset analysis.</li>
						</ul>

						<h3>How updates happen when the inputs change</h3>
						<p>
							If another process writes new files into the expected locations, for example inside
							<code>datasets/</code> or generated content folders, the next build absorbs those changes.
							That build can run once a day, once a week, manually when needed, or from a GitHub Action
							that runs build and deploy at the right moment. GitHub officially documents both
							<code>schedule</code> and <code>workflow_dispatch</code> for scheduled and manual workflow
							runs:
							<a href="https://docs.github.com/actions/reference/events-that-trigger-workflows"> workflow triggers</a>
							y <a href="https://docs.github.com/fr/actions/managing-workflow-runs-and-deployments/managing-workflow-runs/manually-running-a-workflow"> manually running a workflow</a>.
						</p>
						<pre data-language="mermaid"><code>{`flowchart LR
    A["Daily update"] --> E["GitHub Action or local job"]
    B["Weekly update"] --> E
    C["Manual update"] --> E
    D["New data arrives"] --> E
    E --> F["npm run build"]
    F --> G["new dist/ output"]
    G --> H["deploy to bucket"]
`}</code></pre>

						<h3>Why this is still simple to operate</h3>
						<p>
							The system looks more complex because it accepts many inputs, but operationally it is still
							fairly simple: every time the site needs a refresh, the pipeline runs again and replaces the
							static output. There is no need to keep a live backend querying GitHub, reading datasets, or
							rendering Markdown for every visit. That cost happens before publishing, not during traffic.
						</p>

						<h3>Diagram reference</h3>
						<p>
							The diagrams on this page use Mermaid. The official flowchart syntax reference is here:
							<a href="https://mermaid.js.org/syntax/flowchart.html"> Mermaid Flowchart Syntax</a>.
						</p>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section>
					<div class="card-grid">
						{
							featuredRepos.map((repo) => (
								<article class="card">
									<strong>{repo.name}</strong>
									<p>{repo.description}</p>
									<p class="repo-meta">Updated {formatDate(repo.updatedAt)}</p>
									<div class="tag-list">
										{buildRepoTags(repo).map((tag) => (
											<span class="tag">{tag}</span>
										))}
									</div>
									<div class="cta-row">
										<a class="button-link" href={`projects/${repo.slug}.html`}>Read docs</a>
										<a class="button-link" href={repo.repoUrl}>GitHub</a>
									</div>
								</article>
							))
						}
					</div>
				</section>
			</main>
		</div>
	</div>
</Layout>
